{
    "level": "B1",
    "intro": "In this topic you will learn to separate <strong>used to</strong> and <strong>would</strong> for past habits, and to see why past states usually need <strong>used to</strong>.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "PAST HABITS",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "Both <strong>used to</strong> and <strong>would</strong> can describe repeated actions in the past:",
            "example": "When I was a child, I used to / would play outside every day."
        },
        {
            "label": "PAST STATES",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "For past states, situations, and facts, we normally use <strong>used to</strong>, not <strong>would</strong>.",
            "example": "I used to live near the sea."
        },
        {
            "label": "NO LONGER TRUE",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "<strong>Used to</strong> often suggests that the situation is not true now.",
            "example": "She used to smoke."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Main patterns",
    "intro": "Compare the form and the typical meaning.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Habit or state",
            "title": "used to + V1",
            "subtitle": "I used to walk to school. / I used to live there."
        },
        {
            "label": "Repeated action",
            "title": "would + V1",
            "subtitle": "Every summer we would stay with my grandparents."
        },
        {
            "label": "Negative",
            "title": "did not use to + V1",
            "subtitle": "I did not use to like coffee."
        },
        {
            "label": "Question",
            "title": "Did ... use to + V1?",
            "subtitle": "Did you use to play tennis?"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. When to use each one",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Past habits",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "When an action <strong>happened regularly</strong> in the past, both forms are often possible.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Every evening my dad used to read to us.",
                    "ua": "Every evening my dad used to read to us."
                },
                {
                    "en": "On summer evenings we would sit outside for hours.",
                    "ua": "On summer evenings we would sit outside for hours."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She used to call me every Sunday.",
                    "ua": "She used to call me every Sunday."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Past states and situations",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "For <strong>states</strong> such as know, live, be, have, like, we normally choose <strong>used to</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I used to know his sister.",
                    "ua": "I used to know his sister."
                },
                {
                    "en": "They used to have a small shop.",
                    "ua": "They used to have a small shop."
                },
                {
                    "en": "We used to be good friends.",
                    "ua": "We used to be good friends."
                }
            ],
            "note": "Forms like <span class=\"line-through\">would know / would have / would be</span> are usually wrong here."
        },
        {
            "label": "Contrast with Past Simple",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "Past Simple names a past fact, while <strong>used to / would</strong> highlights a habit or repeated pattern.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I visited my grandmother last Sunday.",
                    "ua": "I visited my grandmother last Sunday."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I used to visit my grandmother every Sunday.",
                    "ua": "I used to visit my grandmother every Sunday."
                },
                {
                    "en": "When we were kids, we would build tree houses.",
                    "ua": "When we were kids, we would build tree houses."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Using would for a past state.",
            "wrong": "I would live near the sea when I was a child.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">I used to live near the sea when I was a child.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Wrong form after did.",
            "wrong": "Did you used to play tennis?",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">Did you use to play tennis?</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Using used to for a one-time event.",
            "wrong": "I used to call her yesterday.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">I called her yesterday.</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "4. Quick summary",
    "items": [
        "<strong>Used to</strong> = past habits, states, and situations that are no longer true now.",
        "<strong>Would</strong> = repeated past actions, but not states.",
        "After <strong>did</strong>, use <strong>use to</strong>, not <span class=\"line-through\">used to</span>.",
        "For a one-time finished event, choose Past Simple.",
        "With live / know / be / have / like in the past, <strong>used to</strong> is usually the safe choice."
    ]
}

